Piss, poop, and pot. That's what the outside area of this place smelled like. Obviously, it's the tenderloin, but some of the uninitiated may not be willing to visit. We parked a couple of blocks down, which was a teensy little mistake, but next time I'd make sure to decrease the distance from my car to the front door of this establishment. The wait was shorter than I had anticipated, probably closer to 30 minutes, but I could see that this place gets a lot more busy than that. They offered bar seating or a table, and we asked for a table, so we had to wait a bit longer. Anyway, onto the food: my crawfish beignets were definitely a treat. The different beignets come in 3s, and you can order a sampler of different kinds, which I wish I had done. The reason being, the crawfish beignets were heavy and not as moist as I thought they would be, but still very tasty. But rarely have I ever highlighted drink over food in my reviews, but I have to say--this place had the most refreshing and not too sweet beverage: the watermelon iced tea. From the gods, I'm telling you! I had to get 2 refills and one to go, I was so in love with this drink! A must have when visiting this establishment. Service was slightly more inattentive than I would have liked but hey, the place is busy. I get it. Also, a bit pricey for a breakfast spot, so it's definitely a "once in a while" sorta deal.

Yummy delicious soul food in the city. Service was quick, friendly, personable, and efficient. I came on a Wednesday around noon. Though it was a busy lunch rush, we were sat almost immediately. The mango mimosa recommended by our server Luis was lovely and not overly sweet. The gumbo was delicious-- even without the seafood. The Beignet Flight was nice to try, but nothing mind blowing. It was a bit too dense for my liking... though the crawfish beignet was perfectly executed. I feel the Fried Chicken is overrated. I'm from LA; Roscoe's is better. The Chicken Etouffee was just a watered down version of the gumbo-- pass on this. The real winner was the Shrimp and Grits. 5 stars! I would come back for this dish alone.

so this is what real soul food tastes like? I've been missing out this whole time!!! I walked in with a friend a little before 10:00 AM on a Thursday and got seated quickly. I am so glad we came in at the right time because slowly... people started trickling in and I see a line forming outside! We ordered the following: Crawfish Beignets ($10.50 for 3): this was spiced with cayenne, scallions and cheddar. my god - this was DELICIOUS. When you cut the beignet in half, you see the cheddar and crawfish oozing out - so satisfying! These beignets are HUGE as well. My friend and I actually only finished ONE out of the three! Crispy Pork Belly ($13.50): pork belly with poached egg, cheddar grits and spicy onion relish. The pork belly was super tender and soft - such a perfect combination with the cheddar grits. Every fork of food seriously melted in my mouth! Egg & Bacon Tartine ($10.75): bacon, scrambled eggs, swiss & tomato-bacon relish on toasted french roll with grits. My friend ordered this and she said it was bomb as well! The portions here are HUGE - so be careful not to over order! Well worth the price! The food can get a bit heavy though but hey... that's how soul food is right?!

We bring the church members, we bring friends when they come in from out of town, we being our parents (when we feel like being nice lol), we come and kick it in a cozy corner and just have date dinner here! I don't know. I feel like Yelp needs to take accountability and admit, they misplaced my review. I'm mean really... Moving forward, the food fare that is provided to you at Brenda's is quality Southern goodness. Take it from a real Creole girl. The only thing that Brenda has ran afoul with is her beignet. It's not a beignet. It's a fried, doughy, monstrosity of a pouf with a good savory filling and an okay sweet selection of filings. It's not even "beignet like". There is no reminiscence of a beautiful, light, collapsing texture in chicory coffee beignet. Eat these bad boys with some coffee and you've got one serious brick in your tummy honey! Onward to what is done right: Hey you. The one reading this to figure out if you want to go or not. Let's be honest, you're going to go. It's cool. But can I give you a hint? Get off the menu and go straight to the specials board baby! That's where the line cooks back there really get to shine. Beautiful veggies, a great selection of meat and fish and everything complimentary to that beautiful peach spread sitting in your table! I don't know how she does that. Oh yeah, I do! And I'm not telling. You're just going to have to try it for yourself.

    They came fresh and were warm in the bag. Each bag inside was labeled as to what type of Beignets they were.

    I walked from the Marriott Marquise in Union Square to Brenda's French Soul Food, little did I know I had to walk through the area called "The Tenderloin" which I later found out the other is one of the largest area for drugs and homeless people. When I first came back to the Marriott Marquise,  I told my wife that I have not seen such a large amount of homeless people as when I walked to Brenda's French Soul Food Cafe. Tip for this place, avoid Turk Street and do not look at anyone eye to eye if you want to live.

    Now that I am alive and able to write this review, even though we love Gharadelli Chocolate, the Crawfish Beignets were the best and very tasty, followed closely by the Ghirardelli Chocolate Beignets.
